    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Vnicus mundi Orator, et pragmaticus, sempre mellitus, aut saccharatus:
    						pla[e]runq[ue] diamargaritatus, aut diamoschatus: sa[e]p&egrave; viua ambrosia,	<!-- Terms unclear.-->
    						et nectar de Coelo.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				The unique and pragmatic Orator of the world is always honey-sweet or sugar-sweet:    				
    				[plaerunque diamargaritatus] or thoroughly musky: often, living ambrosia and nectar from heaven.		
    				<!-- CG: I am at a loss with pla[e]runq[ue] (pla[e]runq[uam]?) diamargaritatus. 
    					"Plaerunque" seems wrong, but I'm not sure in what way. 
    					For "diamargaritatus," the Greek root word itself has something to do with pearls,
    					but I have the feeling this refers to some sort of processed extract from a plant or something. --> <!--JG: I think plaerunque is correct, the word does exist. It seems quite rare though, so I haven't been able to find its meaning. Anyway, will send this to the group so that others can have a look at it-->-->
    				<!-- CG: Apparently moschatus is a reference to the sweet seeds of a particular plant from India. The 'dia' functions
    				as an intensifier. -->
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
